    "When TechCorp decided to expand its business, it needed to engage a reliable software supplier. After several rounds of negotiation, both parties reached an agreement on the specific terms of the contract. The legal department spent a week to determine which provisions were essential. They asked the supplier for a written assurance of product quality, and required clauses that obligate the company to provide timely support. To establish a clear framework, the contract included rules that both sides must abide by. For example, prices cannot change during the first year, and any major update requires written approval from both parties. The cancellation clause is also important. Either party may end the agreement with 60 days notice. If disagreements occur, the parties have agreed to resolve disputes through mediation, not litigation. This careful approach protects everyone's interests and gives both companies confidence in a long-term business relationship.": "passage-a-software-licensing-deal.mp3",
    "When a new store opened across the street, our small shop suddenly faced strong competition for the first time in years. Shoppers began to compare our prices with the new store and many of them left without buying anything. We needed a productive plan to attract customers back and remind them why they loved our store in the first place. The team gathered for a brainstorming session, hoping to find inspiration from past success stories and recent customer feedback. We decided to market our products in a fresh way, by featuring real customers sharing their genuine experiences in our ads. We believed that honest stories would be far more persuasion than any flashy promotion or short-lived fad. To convince new shoppers to come in, we also offered free samples and a small discount for first-time visitors. Within a few weeks, more young people came to consume our coffee and pastries, and they started sharing photos online. We are currently tracking customer satisfaction through short surveys at the counter every weekend. The results show that a small, focused effort can win back loyal customers, even when stronger rivals open right across the street.": "passage-winning-back-the-customers.mp3",
    "Mrs. Bordeaux had used her toaster from Kitchen Electronics for nearly a year without any problems. One morning the appliance suddenly stopped working, so she returned the defective unit and asked for a full refund under the one-year warranty. Unfortunately, the customer service manager wrote back to explain that her warranty had expired exactly a month earlier. The terms of the agreement clearly imply that the company will only protect purchases during the active warranty period. Instead of a refund, the manager offered to send her a refurbished toaster of the same model in exchange for the broken one. After considering the offer carefully, Mrs. Bordeaux decided to accept the replacement. The company has a strong reputation, and she had frequently used their kitchen products in the past without any complaint. In fact, this was the first time she had ever experienced a characteristic defect with anything she had bought from them. Before agreeing, she politely required written confirmation that the refurbished unit would carry the same warranty as a brand-new one. Once the manager confirmed the request, both sides closed the case with mutual trust and a fair outcome.": "passage-the-expired-toaster-warranty.mp3",
    "Alexa decided to develop her own business plan after years of working for a large company. Her parents offered to help with market research and to connect her with experienced mentors. They understood that going into business alone carries serious risk, but it can also bring unique rewards. Alexa took the planning process seriously and worked hard to avoid the common mistakes that new entrepreneurs make. She spent weeks gathering information about her competitors, customers, and target audience. Her mentor explained that the most important strategy for success is to start with a sound business plan. The plan needed to address short-term goals, long-term development, and reliable substitutions for key suppliers. Alexa decided that her growth should rely primarily on profits, not on heavy borrowing. She also outlined a clear evaluation method to measure progress at the end of each quarter. By the time she finished, the plan was strong enough to demonstrate her readiness to potential investors.": "passage-alexa-s-business-plan.mp3"
